shared_text:
Governor John Bel Edwards
August 29 at 9:20 AM ·

Today marks 15 years since Hurricane Katrina made landfall. On this day of remembrance, we honor the many lives that were tragically lost in the great City of New Orleans and along the Gulf Coast and hold in prayer the families who still mourn. The impacts remain with us today. Forever changed, we have taken to heart the many important lessons it has taught us. Let us never forget that we are strong and incredibly resilient people who come together in times of need, can come back from a setback and who are proud to call Louisiana home.

August 24 at 5:01 PM ·

Hurricane watches are in place for Southwestern Louisiana. Tropical storm watches are in place for portions of Central and Southeastern Louisiana. Storm surge watches are in place for much of the state's coastline. Heed the directions of local officials and monitor your local news to stay informed on further developments. Follow Louisiana Governor's Office of Homeland Security and Emergency Preparedness, US National Weather Service New Orleans Louisiana, US National Weather Service Lake Charles Louisiana, US National Weather Service Shreveport Louisiana, US National Weather Service Jackson Mississippi and NOAA NWS National Hurricane Center for more updates. #lagov #lawx #Laura

post_text: Thank you to the Kids' Orchestra for finding creative ways to keep music alive for our children during these times! Music, arts, and movement are critical in developing the whole child. 🎶🎵 #TeachMAMTuesday
shared_text:
Kids' Orchestra is at undefined.
July 31 at 12:00 PM ·

We are proud of present our 2020 KO@Home Concerts Showcase! 🌟

Our KO@Home Concerts Showcase is a virtual adaption of our Spring Neighborhood Concert Series.

Launched in response to the COVID-19 pandemic, KO@Home is our virtual learning program and KO@Home Concerts served as the culminating experience for our enrolled students, allowing them to put on a performance at home for their families.

Now, with our first ever KO@Home Concerts Showcase, our students can share their hard work with YOU!

Please join us in celebrating our students and the power of music by watching and sharing our Showcase video. 🎶

💙 Thank you to our many supporters for keeping music alive, including Aetna Better Health of Louisiana, Junior League of Baton Rouge, Rotary Club of Baton Rouge Foundation, Louisiana Division of the Arts, the Arts Council of Greater Baton Rouge, and the National Endowment for the Arts, among others. 💙

#KOProud #KOathome #KeepMusicAlive

shared_text:
Governor John Bel Edwards
July 20 at 8:18 AM ·

Starting today, I am beginning three days of fasting and prayer for our state through July 22. The people of Louisiana need our prayers right now.

If you are inclined, please join me, First Lady Donna Edwards and faith leaders from across Louisiana in prayerful reflection and fasting on these three days. I encourage and welcome people of all faiths and denominations to participate.

I believe in the power of prayer and I believe in the power of working together and being good neighbors to overcome COVID-19. As the Bible says: Faith without works is dead. #lagov

shared_text:
Governor John Bel Edwards
July 18 at 5:31 PM ·

Today, I issued an executive order that flags be flown at half-staff in honor of the life and legacy of Rep. John Lewis, civil rights pioneer and icon. Congressman Lewis is an icon of the American Civil Rights Movement and dedicated his life to protecting human rights, securing civil liberties, and building what he called “The Beloved Community” in America.

As he poignantly once said, ‘When we see something that’s not right, or not just, we have a moral obligation to speak up and speak out to do something about it.’ He will be long remembered by the people of Louisiana and across the world.

Please join First Lady Donna Edwards and me in praying for Congressman Lewis’ family and all who have been touched by his tremendous fight for justice and equality for all of humanity. #lagov

shared_text:
Volunteers In Public Schools
July 14 at 2:05 PM ·

Check out our interview with the amazing First Lady Donna Edwards as she discusses her experience as a Super Summer Reader! In order to combat summer reading loss, especially during the summer VIPS advanced "Super Summer Readers". Along with storytime videos from community leaders, VIPS distributes books to the 100 children from a designated school. This rewarding book distribution allows children who may be void of an adult to read to them at home, to read along with the Super Summer Readers.

Thank you Lady Edwards for being apart of our objective! Interested in becoming a partner? Visit our website at vipsbr.org, also subscribe to our channel at VIPSBatonRouge to watch storytimes of Lady Edwards and more!

https://youtu.be/EsMQbsJcyEk

shared_text:
Governor John Bel Edwards
June 19 at 12:00 PM ·

I have declared today, June 19, 2020, as Juneteenth Observance Day in Louisiana. On Juneteenth, we celebrate the end of slavery in America and we honor the history and contributions of African Americans in our country.

Juneteenth is a celebration of freedom and justice and it is a reminder of the strength and resolve of African Americans throughout history.

Honoring Juneteenth gives us all an opportunity to develop a greater and deeper understanding and appreciation of the experiences of African Americans. As we take time to reflect today, may we all recommit ourselves to the ongoing fight for equity and justice. #Juneteenth #lagov

📰: gov.la.gov/Juneteenth

As today marks the beginning of the 2020 Hurricane Season, we are actively monitoring a tropical system in the Bay of Campeche with a high probability of development. Regardless of development, there will be a potential for heavy rainfall this weekend.

I want to urge the people of Louisiana to prepare for hurricane season now and Get A Game Plan. Visit GetAGameplan.org for emergency preparedness tips and information and be sure to add items like masks and hand sanitizer into your supplies kit.

There is still significant uncertainty in the system's eventual track and intensity, but we will continue to monitor the situation and offer updates as they are made available. Follow Louisiana Governor's Office of Homeland Security and Emergency Preparedness, NOAA NWS National Hurricane Center and US National Weather Service New Orleans Louisiana for important updates and info. #lagov #lawx

Governor John Bel Edwards
May 15 at 6:08 PM ·

Congratulations, class of 2020! I know this isn’t the senior year you envisioned and no one can replace the memories you had hoped to share with friends and family during this time. But, I want you to know how incredibly proud I am of everything you have accomplished and the persistence it took to get there.

One of the things our fight against COVID-19 has taught us is that we need creative, innovative minds like yours to bring forth solutions and build stronger communities no matter what challenges come our way. You are the future of Louisiana, and because of you, that future looks bright.

One day when we can all be together again, we will ensure that your class is properly celebrated. #lagov

THEADVOCATE.COM
One of two BRPD officers dies from injuries in Conrad Drive shooting; suspect taken into custody

Governor John Bel Edwards
April 26 at 6:39 PM ·

Our hearts are heavy today as we mourn the loss of a dedicated public servant who made the ultimate sacrifice for the people of Baton Rouge and the State of Louisiana. This officer protected and served the Baton Rouge community for more than 20 years, and we will never be able to fully repay him for his heroism and commitment to keeping us safe.

May we also take the time to pause and lift up in prayer the injured officer who is currently fighting for his life in the hospital.

It is a dark day in our state, and First Lady Donna Edwards and I send our prayers to the family and friends of both officers and to the entire Baton Rouge Police Department and law enforcement community during this difficult time. #lagov

shared_text:
Governor John Bel Edwards
April 22 at 6:08 PM ·

Part of our new normal will mean wearing a mask or face-covering in public. Wearing a mask in public is just like holding a door open for someone, it's being kind and courteous, and it will be critical to Louisiana moving forward.

When I say mask, I mean wearing some sort of cloth facial covering. We've seen creative folks make masks out of t-shirts or other household materials, and I am encouraging everyone to begin the process now to start getting them for yourselves and your families.

Take this time to make sure you and everyone in your family has a face covering, you can buy or make masks. Remember, unless you are a healthcare worker, you do not need to wear or purchase N95 or surgical masks. #lagov #MaskUpLa

GOV.LOUISIANA.GOV
Gov. Edwards Declares State of Emergency Following Sunday’s Severe Weather, Tornadoes | Office of Governor John Bel Edwards

Governor John Bel Edwards
April 12 at 8:06 PM ·

Today, I declared a State of Emergency following severe weather in the state, which included large hail and several strong tornadoes. The damage is devastating and is a good reminder that everyone should stay weather aware.

Sunday’s severe weather impacted multiple parishes, with reported tornadoes and hail. I am declaring this emergency in order to make sure the impacted parishes and any additional areas that may see severe weather into the night are able to get assistance.

Please continue to monitor local media for information about weather in your area and follow the directions of your local officials. #lagov #lawx

I hope all of Louisiana is on high alert right now. Even though the morning storms have left the state, many other dangerous systems remain across Louisiana. Please stay at home, follow the orders of local officials and tune in to your local weather person for updates. #lagov #lawx

shared_text:
NOLA.COM
Louisiana lawmaker Reggie Bagala dies amid battle with coronavirus at age 54

Governor John Bel Edwards
April 9 at 7:14 PM ·

A successful businessman, devoted family man, and active volunteer, Rep. Bagala spent his life making his community and south Louisiana a better place to live for everyone. Just one month ago, he entered the Louisiana State Capitol with excitement and eagerness to serve the people of our great state and the people of House District 54, and today we mourn his loss.

We are better for having people like Rep. Bagala who are willing to be public servants and make our state better. I ask the people of Louisiana to join Donna and me in praying for Rep. Bagala's family, friends, colleagues and the people of House District 54 during this difficult time. #lagov

Welcome to the first lesson in a guided music lesson series for beginning band students to discover their sound from Teach MAM Ambassador and GRAMMY Music Educator Mickey Smith Jr. 🎵

Upon completion of this lesson students should be able to demonstrate an understanding of the following:
Staff
Measure (bar)
Bar Line
Whole Note

Today, we are announcing a new text alert system that will provide timely COVID-19 updates and other critical guidance directly from the governor’s office to Louisiana residents.

I encourage all Louisianans to sign-up for the new text alert system and stay up to date with the latest COVID-19 information. We are all in this together, and having the most recent information is critical in stopping the spread of COVID-19 throughout Louisiana.

We have not yet begun to flatten the curve in Louisiana, and we need the people of our great state to be good neighbors, stay at home and socially distance themselves now more than ever.

To opt-in, text ‘LACOVID’ to 67283.

#lagov #lalege

shared_text:
Governor John Bel Edwards
March 19 at 1:42 PM ·

Big news! More than 440,000 small businesses in all 64 Louisiana parishes will have access to federal Small Business Administration disaster aid in the wake of the COVID-19 crisis. COVID-19 is a unique crisis affecting all walks of life, and that means Louisiana’s small business community will continue to be heavily impacted by disruptions to their operations.

We are pleased to work with SBA and the federal government in providing this critical working capital to our small business owners who are suffering from the necessary measures installed due to the Coronavirus. Our hope is that these SBA disaster loans will be an important part of sustaining their businesses and providing support to their employees who make up over half of Louisiana’s private-sector workforce. #lagov

📰: https://gov.louisiana.gov/index.cfm/newsroom/detail/2419

State of Louisiana Reports Second COVID-19 Related Death | Office of Governor John Bel Edwards

Governor John Bel Edwards
March 15 at 9:30 AM ·

Sadly, we have lost our second Louisianan to COVID-19. I ask the people of Louisiana to join us in sending thoughts and prayers to the family members and friends who have lost their loved one.

As the number of positive cases continues to rise, we need every person to take the necessary actions to help reduce the spread of this virus. It is an extremely serious situation that demands all of our attention.

Our elderly and those with chronic health conditions are the most vulnerable, but we all need to act responsibly and look out for ourselves and our neighbors. #lagov #COVID19

shared_text:
GOV.LOUISIANA.GOV
State of Louisiana Reports First COVID-19 Related Death | Office of Governor John Bel Edwards

Governor John Bel Edwards
March 14 at 4:13 PM ·

It is with heavy hearts that we announce the first Louisiana death related to COVID-19 today. I have spoken with Mayor LaToya Cantrell, and we send our prayers and condolences to the family of the deceased. In addition, we now have 10 new presumptive positive cases bringing our total to 77.

Now more than ever, we must remain vigilant against the spread of this illness by taking care of ourselves and each other, avoiding going into public areas if you are sick, practicing social distancing and washing your hands frequently with soap and water.

This underscores the fact that those with underlying health issues are most at risk from the coronavirus. Those with compromised immune systems and are older should be taking extra precautions to avoid becoming affected with the coronavirus. #lagov

shared_text:
Governor John Bel Edwards
March 13 at 1:07 PM ·

Today, I signed a proclamation that immediately halts any gathering of more than 250 people until Monday, April 13, closes all K-12 public schools statewide effective Monday, March 16 and also moves upcoming state elections.

We are at an inflection point now and we are going to take bold action to minimize the further spread of this illness. That is why I am issuing this order today, ending all events of more than 250 people, closing our schools, and reducing the amount of face-to-face public interaction at state government buildings.

In a separate executive order I will grant Secretary of State Kyle Ardoin’s request to move our upcoming elections for April and May to June and July. The limits on gatherings of 250 people or more statewide is based on federal CDC guidance given the community spread which we are currently experiencing. These steps are necessary to protect the health and safety of the people of Louisiana from the risk of COVID-19.

📰: https://gov.louisiana.gov/index.cfm/newsroom/detail/2403

shared_text:
Governor John Bel Edwards
March 9 at 2:04 PM ·

Today, the Louisiana Department of Health has reported Louisiana’s first presumptive positive case of COVID-19, commonly referred to as coronavirus, as a Jefferson Parish resident who is hospitalized in Orleans Parish.

At this time, there is only one known case of the illness in the state.

While today is the first time that we can confirm that we have a presumptive positive coronavirus case, Louisiana has been preparing for this moment for many weeks. The CDC still believes the risk to the general public is low, but we will work quickly and decisively to assess the risk to those around this patient. #lagov

📰: https://gov.louisiana.gov/index.cfm/newsroom/category/9

shared_text:
KATC.COM
Longtime Louisiana legislator Butch Gautreaux has died

Governor John Bel Edwards
February 24 at 1:39 PM ·

First Lady Donna Edwards and I send our prayers to Butch Gautreaux’s family. He was a dear friend who supported me in every way possible. I’ll always be grateful to him for his kindness, counsel & the fun times we had at the Shrimp and Petroleum Festival. Butch loved his community and worked tirelessly to help improve the lives of the people he served across our state. We have lost a true giant who understood that people are always more important than politics. In lieu of flowers, the family requests the consideration of a donation to the Nicholls State University Foundation Scholarship fund in memory of Butch. Please go to nichollsfoundation.org and specify your donation to the “Butch Gautreaux Scholarship fund”.

post_text: Thank you so much for having me! And thank you for the work y'all are doing every day to end the cycle of child abuse and protect Louisiana's children. Your work is an inspiration to us all! ❤️
shared_text:
Children's Advocacy Center-Hope House
February 18 at 11:57 AM ·

We had a very special visitor at Hope House yesterday! It was an honor to welcome Louisiana’s First Lady Donna Edwards to our Children’s Advocacy Center. It was an afternoon filled with thoughtful conversation. Mrs. Edwards truly understands the critical importance of our work and how it affects the entire trajectory of a child’s life. During her visit, she met with each staff member, and got to know more about each of our valuable programs for evidence collection, trauma-informed licensed therapy, victim advocacy and child abuse prevention. We are so appreciative of Mrs. Edwards’ continued advocacy and support for our mission to end child abuse, and bring justice and healing to victims across the Northshore.❤️

post_text: At just six years old, Ruby Bridges became the first African American student to integrate an elementary school in the South when she attended an all-white school in New Orleans. In her own words, “Don’t follow the path. Go where there is no path and begin the trail. When you start a new trail equipped with courage, strength and conviction, the only thing that can stop you is you!” #MotivationalMonday #BlackHistoryMonth

post_text:
What a wonderful ride it’s been with my best friend. 30 years of marriage, 3 wonderful children, 4 years in the Governor’s Mansion, and he’s still the same John Bel I knew in the 7th grade (and he still loves his truck!)

Louisiana, thank you from the bottom of my heart. Thank you for trusting my sweetheart to lead our state these last 4 years, and thank you for trusting me to serve as your First Lady. I have loved every minute of working with you to make Louisiana a better place for our children and families, and I am so hopeful for the progress we will make in these next 4 years.

I can’t wait to continue this journey with you, @LousianaGov!

THEADVOCATE.COM
Louisiana state governments under cyber attack

Governor John Bel Edwards
November 18, 2019 at 5:42 PM ·

Today, we activated the state's cybersecurity team in response to an attempted ransomware attack that is affecting some state servers. The Office of Technology Services identified a cybersecurity threat that affected some, but not all state servers. The service interruption was due to OTS’ aggressive response to prevent additional infection of state servers and not due to the attempted ransomware attack. Online services started to come back online this afternoon, though full restoration may take several days. There is no anticipated data loss and the state did not pay a ransom. Louisiana State Police and several federal agencies are investigating this attempted ransomware attack. #lagov

FOX8LIVE.COM
New Orleans area businessman Ray Brandt dies at 72

Governor John Bel Edwards
November 15, 2019 at 12:12 PM ·

First Lady Donna Edwards and I send our deepest condolences to the family of Ray Brandt. A true believer in providing a quality education for all of our children, he served our state faithfully as a long time member of the Louisiana Board of Regents and as chairman of the Louisiana Motor Vehicle Commission. He also lived to celebrate our culture and just a few years ago he served as king of the Mystick Krewe of Louisianans during the Washington DC Mardi Gras. Ray’s impact on our state will be remembered for many years to come. Please join us in prayer for his wife Jessica and their family and friends. #lagov

shared_text:
GOV.LOUISIANA.GOV
Governor Edwards Issues Statement on Louisiana’s GDP Growth and Continued Record High GDP | Office of Governor John Bel Edwards

Governor John Bel Edwards
November 7, 2019 at 2:30 PM ·

Great news! According to the Bureau of Economic Analysis, Louisiana’s GDP grew at a rate of 1.7%, the 29th fastest in the nation and the highest state GDP on record, outpacing other Southern states like Georgia, Kentucky & North Carolina. Louisiana continues to see growth in its gross domestic product, which is at a record high level and growing faster than many other states. We’re on the right track in Louisiana and growing stronger every day. Just last night, in fact, the White House praised Louisiana’s economic performance, saying our state is ‘booming’. #lagov

shared_text:
THEADVOCATE.COM
Report: Acclaimed author, Louisianian Ernest Gaines dies

Governor John Bel Edwards
November 5, 2019 at 3:16 PM ·

It is with a heavy heart that we say goodbye to Ernest J. Gaines, a native Louisianan who used his immense vision and literary talents to tell the stories of African Americans in the South. We are all blessed that Ernest left words and stories that will continue to inspire many generations to come. Born in poverty in Pointe Coupee, Ernest would go on to author 10 novels and numerous short stories, to be nominated for a Pulitzer Prize and win the National Book Critics Circle Award for his acclaimed novel A Lesson Before Dying. He was a writer in residence at the University of Louisiana at Lafayette for more than 20 years. Earlier this year, Donna and I had the chance to visit with Ernest and his wife after a Sunday drive. It’s a memory we will both cherish as part of our long friendship. Please join us in elevating him, his wife and his family in your prayers. #lagov

National report highlights Louisiana’s progress in closing the K-12 digital divide | Minden Press-Herald

Governor John Bel Edwards
October 25, 2019 at 12:00 PM ·

Great news! 100 percent of K-12 students in Louisiana now have access to high-speed broadband on par with the FCC’s minimum bandwidth goal per student, which ensures expanded opportunities for teaching and learning in Louisiana’s classrooms. We must continue this incredible progress connecting our students to next-generation broadband so they have access to online educational resources and tools in every classroom, every day to compete for 21st-century jobs. #lagov

shared_text:
WGNO.COM
LA unemployment at 11-year low, New Orleans employment highest since Hurricane Katrina, Baton Rouge employment at record high

Governor John Bel Edwards
October 18, 2019 at 1:32 PM ·

Big news! Louisiana’s unemployment rate of 4.3% is at an 11-year low, with job gains in New Orleans pushing its employment to the highest level since Hurricane Katrina and employment in Baton Rouge now at the highest recorded level. This is amazing economic news not only for this area, but for our state, which is also experiencing its highest GDP and personal income on record. Not to be left out, the BLS data released today shows Baton Rouge has its highest employment on record as well. This is why I am bullish on our future in Louisiana – we are adding jobs, our economy is growing and our people are taking home more money in their paychecks. #lagov
